If you'd like, I can also explain how a packet travels from your laptop to Google step by step through all 7 OSI layers, which makes the model much easier to remember.
yes
Great! Let's follow a real packet from your laptop to Google and see what happens at each OSI layer.

Suppose you open a browser and type:
https://www.google.com

Step 1: Application Layer (Layer 7)
Your browser creates an HTTP request:
GET / HTTP/1.1
Host: www.google.com
This is the actual message you want to send.
Think:
"I want Google's homepage."

Step 2: Presentation Layer (Layer 6)
Since you're using HTTPS, the data is encrypted using TLS/SSL.
Before encryption:
GET / HTTP/1.1
Host: www.google.com
After encryption:
8h3K#@2LmP...
Anyone intercepting the traffic sees only encrypted data.

Step 3: Session Layer (Layer 5)
A communication session is established between:
Your Browser <-----> Google Server
The session layer helps maintain and manage this conversation.

Step 4: Transport Layer (Layer 4)
The Transport Layer uses TCP.
First, TCP establishes a connection using the 3-way handshake:
Laptop                        Google
SYN       ------------------->
          <------------------- SYN-ACK
ACK       ------------------->

Connection established.

Now TCP adds:

Source Port      : 50000
Destination Port : 443

Example:
192.168.1.10:50000 ---> Google:443
Port 443 means HTTPS.

Step 5: Network Layer (Layer 3)
Now an IP header is added.
Example:

Source IP      : 192.168.1.10
Destination IP : 142.250.183.36

(One of Google's IP addresses)

Packet becomes:

Source IP      : 192.168.1.10
Destination IP : 142.250.183.36
TCP Port       : 443
Data           : Encrypted HTTP Request

Routers use this information to decide where to send the packet.

Step 6: Data Link Layer (Layer 2)
Now MAC addresses are added.
Example:
Source MAC      : AA:BB:CC:DD:EE:FF
Destination MAC : 11:22:33:44:55:66
These MAC addresses are used only on the local network.
The packet is now inside an Ethernet frame.

Step 7: Physical Layer (Layer 1)
The frame is converted into actual signals:
Electrical signals (Ethernet cable)
Light signals (Fiber)
Radio waves (Wi-Fi)

These signals travel to your router.

Journey Through the Internet

Your home router receives the packet.

Laptop
   |
   v
Home Router
   |
   v
ISP
   |
   v
Internet Routers
   |
   v
Google Network
   |
   v
Google Server

At each router:
Layer 2 information changes
Layer 3 IP addresses remain the same
Routers use the destination IP to forward the packet.

At Google's Server
The server receives the packet and removes the headers in reverse order.
Layer 1 -> Layer 2 -> Layer 3 -> Layer 4 -> Layer 5 -> Layer 6 -> Layer 7
This process is called decapsulation.

Finally Google sees:
GET / HTTP/1.1
Host: www.google.com
Google processes the request and sends a response back.


Encapsulation and Decapsulation

When sending:

Application Data
      |
      v
+------------------+
| Layer 7 Data     |
+------------------+
| Layer 4 Header   |
+------------------+
| Layer 3 Header   |
+------------------+
| Layer 2 Header   |
+------------------+
| Physical Signals |
+------------------+

This is called encapsulation.

When receiving:

Remove Layer 2 Header
Remove Layer 3 Header
Remove Layer 4 Header
Decrypt Data
Deliver to Application

This is called decapsulation.

