what is meant by host based and path based routing:

1. Host-Based Routing

Host-based routing uses the Host header (domain name) to decide where to send traffic.

| Host Name         | Target Group  |
| ----------------- | ------------- |
| company.com       | Web Servers   |
| api.company.com   | API Servers   |
| admin.company.com | Admin Servers |

Example Request

GET /
Host: api.company.com
ALB sees:
Host = api.company.com
and forwards traffic to:
API Target Group

2. Path-Based Routing
Path-based routing uses the URL path to decide where to send traffic.
Suppose all traffic uses the same domain:
company.com
but different paths.

| Path      | Target Group    |
| --------- | --------------- |
| /products | Product Service |
| /orders   | Order Service   |
| /payments | Payment Service |

Request 1:
GET /products
Host: company.com
ALB routes to:
Product Service


Host-Based + Path-Based Together
You can combine both.
Example:
| Host              | Path      | Destination   |
| ----------------- | --------- | ------------- |
| api.company.com   | /users/*  | User Service  |
| api.company.com   | /orders/* | Order Service |
| admin.company.com | /*        | Admin Service |



Easy Way to Think About It
Every HTTP request contains both:
Host
Path
Example:
https://www.amazon.com/orders
contains:
Host = www.amazon.com
Path = /orders
The difference is:
Host-Based Routing
ALB decision:
Look at Host
Ignore Path

Path-Based Routing
ALB decision:
Look at Path
Ignore Host (or Host is same for everyone)

Combined Routing
ALB decision:
Look at Host
AND
Look at Path





understanding of http protocol and TCP, UDP protocols and data transfer :
------------------------------------------------------------------------

1. What is HTTP Traffic?
HTTP traffic is the actual web communication between a browser and a web server.

2. What is TCP Traffic?
TCP stands for:
Transmission Control Protocol
TCP is responsible for transporting data reliably.

HTTP
The letter:
Dear Amazon,
Show me my orders.

TCP
The courier company:
Collect letter
Transport letter
Confirm delivery

The letter is HTTP.
The courier is TCP.


Web Page
When you open:
https://amazon.com

Protocol stack:

HTTPS  (Layer 7)
   ↓
TCP    (Layer 4)
   ↓
IP     (Layer 3)


Downloading an Image
HTTPS  (Layer 7)
   ↓
TCP    (Layer 4)
   ↓
IP     (Layer 3)
Same stack.

Watching a YouTube Video
HTTPS  (Layer 7)
   ↓
TCP    (Layer 4)
   ↓
IP     (Layer 3)
Still the same stack.

Zoom / Google Meet
These real-time applications often use:
WebRTC (Layer 7)
   ↓
UDP    (Layer 4)
   ↓
IP     (Layer 3)
UDP is chosen because low latency is more important than perfect reliability.
HTTP always uses a transport protocol (typically TCP). Whether the content is text, HTML, images, or video does not change the fact that HTTP traffic is carried by TCP.

